docs.abstract: The choreographer Mariana Valencia has gone from making “abstract quiet dances” to using autobiography to engage, often in comic ways, with audiences.
docs.snippet: The choreographer Mariana Valencia has gone from making “abstract quiet dances” to using autobiography to engage, often in comic ways, with audiences.
docs.lead_paragraph: Growing up in Chicago in the 1980s, the choreographer Mariana Valencia began making dance steps long before she knew what choreography was. From the ages of 2 to 5, she had a recurring gig on public access television, as a guest on the Spanish-language children’s show “El Club del Niño.”

headline.main: What if a Dance Piece Were Actually Funny? Or Super Sad?

docs.abstract: More than 18,000 women are expected to receive $2,500 to $250,000 from the University of Southern California.
docs.snippet: More than 18,000 women are expected to receive $2,500 to $250,000 from the University of Southern California.
docs.lead_paragraph: A federal judge in Los Angeles said this week that he was inclined to give final approval to the University of Southern California’s $215 million class-action settlement with former patients of Dr. George Tyndall, the campus gynecologist accused of sexual misconduct involving hundreds of patients during his decades-long tenure.

headline.main: Judge Signals Approval of U.S.C.’s $215 Million Settlement With Ex-Gynecologist’s Patients
